\f[B]\f[CB]total_client_connections\f[B]\f[R]
total number of client connections
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]total_cr_infos\f[B]\f[R]
total sum of a number of destinations queried by each client connection
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]total_oid_infos\f[B]\f[R]
total number of oids requested and returned to a client
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]total_sid_infos\f[B]\f[R]
total number of SNMP requests performed
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]total_timers_sec\f[B]\f[R]
total number of timer slots with a second resolution
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]total_timers_usec\f[B]\f[R]
total number of timers
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]udp_receive_buffer_size\f[B]\f[R]
the size of UDP receive buffer for SNMP socket
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]udp_send_buffer_size\f[B]\f[R]
the size of UDP send buffer for SNMP socket
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]udp_send_buffer_overflow\f[B]\f[R]
number of times a UDP packet could not be sent due to a send buffer
overflow
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]udp_timeouts\f[B]\f[R]
total number of \(lqsoft\(rq timeouts
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]uptime\f[B]\f[R]
daemon uptime in milliseconds
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]v3_engineid_discoveries\f[B]\f[R]
number of times an SNMPv3 engine ID was discovered from an agent (see
the \f[CR]engineid\f[R] option of the \f[B]SETOPT\f[R] request)
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]v3_engineid_mismatches\f[B]\f[R]
number of requests failed with an \f[CR]engine\-id\-mismatch\f[R] error
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]program_version\f[B]\f[R]
numeric version of the engine program (frozen; see
\f[B]\f[CB]version\f[B]\f[R])
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]version\f[B]\f[R]
version of the engine program, as a semantic versioning string (present
in global stats only)
.SS GET
Clients should use the \f[B]GET\f[R] request to obtain one or more oids
from a destination.
A single \f[B]GET\f[R] request will correspond to one or more SNMP gets,
depending on the values of \f[I]\f[CI]max_req_size\f[I]\f[R],
\f[I]\f[CI]max_reply_size\f[I]\f[R],
\f[I]\f[CI]estimated_value_size\f[I]\f[R], and
\f[I]\f[CI]max_oids_per_request\f[I]\f[R] options.
.PP
GET parameters:
.TP
parameter 2
destination IP (v4 only) address in a dot\-decimal notation
.TP
parameter 3
destination port number
.TP
parameter 4
an array of oids to get
.PP
\f[B]GET\f[R] reply consists of an array, each element of which
corresponds to a single requested oid.
Each such element is itself a two\-element array.
The first element will be oid itself.
The second element will either be a value, or an array with a single
element.
If it is an array, its only element will be an error description.
Possible errors are:
.TP
no\-such\-object
SNMP reply returned \(lqno such object\(rq for this oid
.TP
no\-such\-instance
SNMP reply returned \(lqno such instance\(rq for this oid
.TP
end\-of\-mib
SNMP reply returned \(lqend\-of\-mib\(rq for this oid
.TP
timeout
there was a timeout; for \f[B]GET\f[R] requests with a small number of
oids, in case of timeout all oids will generally return this error; for
larger \f[B]GET\f[R] requests, it is perfectly possible to get this
error for only some of the oids
.TP
ignored
the oid was requested during time when its destination was in the
\(lqignore\(rq state (see \f[CR]ignore_threshold\f[R] and
\f[CR]ignore_duration\f[R] options for details)
.TP
missing
the oid not found in the reply
.TP
decode\-error
there was an error decoding the value
.TP
unsupported type 0xHH
the \f[CR]snmp\-query\-engine\f[R] does not support values of this type
(yet)
.TP
engine\-id\-mismatch: HEX
the agent (or something claiming to be it) reported an SNMP engine ID
different from the configured or previously discovered one; HEX is the
engine ID the peer claimed
.TP
kul\-calculation\-error
localizing the configured SNMPv3 passwords to keys failed after engine
ID discovery
.PP
Example request:
.IP
.EX
[GET, $id, \(dq127.0.0.1\(dq, 161,
   [ \(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0\(dq,
     \(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.25.1.1.0\(dq,
     \(dq1.3.66\(dq ]
]
.EE
.PP
Example reply:
.IP
.EX
[GET|0x10, $id, [
   [\(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0\(dq, \(dqmy.host.name\(dq],
   [\(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.25.1.1.0\(dq, 215485727],
   [\(dq1.3.66\(dq, [\(dqno\-such\-object\(dq]],
 ],
]
.EE
.SS GETTABLE
Clients should use the \f[B]GETTABLE\f[R] request to obtain a table of
oids from a destination.
A single \f[B]GETTABLE\f[R] request will correspond to one or more SNMP
get\-next (for SNMP version 1) or get\-bulk (for SNMP version 2)
queries.
.PP
GETTABLE parameters:
.TP
parameter 2
destination IP (v4 only) address in a dot\-decimal notation
.TP
parameter 3
destination port number
.TP
parameter 4
an oid of a table to get
.PP
\f[B]GETTABLE\f[R] reply consists of an array, each element of which
corresponds to a single oid from the requested table.
Each such element is itself a two\-element array.
The first element will be oid itself.
The second element will either be a value, or an array with a single
element.
If it is an array, its only element will be an error description.
Possible errors are the same as in \f[B]GET\f[R] request, plus the
following error specific to \f[B]GETTABLE\f[R]:
.TP
non\-increasing
this oid is less than or equal than the previous oid in the table; there
will be no further attempts to continue iterating the table
.PP
In practice, the \(lqno\-such\-object\(rq and \(lqno\-such\-instance\(rq
errors never occur in \f[B]GETTABLE\f[R] replies, because the underlying
SNMP get\-next and get\-bulk queries do not produce them.
.PP
A successful reply with an empty array means that no oids exist under
the requested oid.
This happens both when the table is empty and when the destination does
not implement the table at all: SNMP get\-next and get\-bulk queries
cannot distinguish between these two cases, so, unlike \f[B]GET\f[R], an
attempt to walk a non\-existent table is not reported as a
\(lqno\-such\-object\(rq error.
.PP
The requested table oid is never present in the reply itself if there
were no errors.
.PP
Example request 1:
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE, $id, \(dq127.0.0.1\(dq, 161, \(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5\(dq]
.EE
.PP
Example reply 1:
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE|0x10, $id, [[\(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0\(dq, \(dqmy.host.name\(dq]]]
.EE
.PP
Example request 2:
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE, $id, \(dq127.0.0.1\(dq, 161, \(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0\(dq]
.EE
.PP
Example reply 2 (\(lqno oids under the requested oid\(rq \- here because
a leaf oid was requested; an empty or non\-existent table produces the
same reply):
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE|0x10, $id, []]
.EE
.PP
Example request 3:
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE, $id, \(dq1.1.1.1\(dq, 161, \(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5\(dq]
.EE
.PP
Example reply 3 (\(lqtable oid itself in error reply\(rq):
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE|0x10, 41, [[\(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5\(dq, [\(dqtimeout\(dq]]]]
.EE
.PP
Example request 4:
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE, $id, \(dqip\-of\-some\-misbehaving\-host\(dq, 161, \(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5\(dq]
.EE
.PP
Example reply 4:
.IP
.EX
[GETTABLE|0x10, $id, [
  [\(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0\(dq, \(dqmy.host.name\(dq],
  [\(dq1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0\(dq, [\(dqnon\-increasing\(dq]],
]]
.EE
.SS DEST INFO
The \f[B]DEST INFO\f[R] request allows the client to request
per\-destination statistics.
.PP
DEST INFO parameters:
.TP
parameter 2
destination IP (v4 only) address in a dot\-decimal notation
.TP
parameter 3
destination port number
.PP
\f[B]DEST INFO\f[R] reply will consist of a map per\-destination
statistics.
.PP
The following statistics are available:
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]octets_received\f[B]\f[R]
number of payload octets received from the destination
.TP
\f[B]\f[CB]octets_sent\f[B]\f[R]
number of payload octets sent to the destination
.SH SEE ALSO
There is a Perl module which serves as a client to
\f[CR]snmp\-query\-engine\f[R],
\f[B]Net::SNMP::QueryEngine::AnyEvent\f[R].
It can be found on CPAN and on github.
